After the 2017 Women’s March, women kept stopping Cecile Richards on the street, on the subway, at events.
“We had this sense that women were on fire and ready to take action,” Garza says.
The name is a nod to the numbers: Women, Richards says, comprise not just the majority of voters in this country, but also the majority of activists.
And yet the issues that impact women the most — reproductive health care, equal pay, child care, sexual violence — are treated as ancillary in the political conversation.
Its goal is to organize 2 million women ahead of the election with voter education, registration, and turnout drives.